      <byline class="print_byline">By ELISABETH GINSBURG</byline>
      <byline class="normalized_byline">Ginsburg, Elisabeth</byline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Fall is good time to plant perennials and spring-flowering bulbs (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>Fall planting makes eminent good sense. Gardeners are less likely to overheat and perennials are more likely to get a head start on next year.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>Fall planting makes eminent good sense. Gardeners are less likely to overheat and perennials are more likely to get a head start on next year.</p>
        <p>Since fall is also a busy time, it makes sense to plant those newly acquired perennials as you sow the spring bulbs. If you choose spreading perennials such as Geranium macrorrhizum, you will also be providing a modicum of coverage for next summer's dying bulb foliage. Assemble the bulbs that you want to plant, along with a 1-quart pot of a dependable perennial of your choice. Dig a trench deep enough to accommodate the perennial and the bulbs. Plop your perennial in the middle and place the bulbs in groups on either side, or all around it.  Refill the whole trench with soil. You have just solved several garden problems in one easy step.</p>
        <p>ELISABETH GINSBURG</p>
        <p>CLIPPINGS</p>
      </block>
